{"id": 27052, "date": "1987-01-08T11:00:00", "date_gmt": "1987-01-08T19:00:00", "guid": {"rendered": "https://estreetshuffle.com/?p=27052"}, "modified": "2026-06-03T17:05:32", "modified_gmt": "2026-06-04T00:05:32", "slug": "matr-bruce-springsteen-paul-simon-billy-joel-james-taylor-and-more-rock-and-roll-music", "status": "publish", "type": "post", "link": "https://estreetshuffle.com/index.php/1987/01/08/matr-bruce-springsteen-paul-simon-billy-joel-james-taylor-and-more-rock-and-roll-music/", "title": {"rendered": "Rock and Roll Music"}, "content": {"rendered": "<p>The first time Bruce Springsteen performed with Chuck Berry, the rock pioneer had no idea who Bruce was. That&#8217;s understandable, though&#8211;in April 1973, hardly anyone did.</p>\n<p>But when Bruce and his band (they didn&#8217;t even have a name at the time, that&#8217;s how early this was) were hired to open for Berry, Bruce begged the promoter to let his band back the headliner for his set, too.</p>\n<p>Let&#8217;s let Bruce pick up the story from here:</p>\n<div id=\"v-1Xt1C7qI-1\" class=\"video-player\"><iframe title='VideoPress Video Player' aria-label='VideoPress Video Player' width='758' height='424' src='https://videopress.com/embed/1Xt1C7qI?hd=1&amp;cover=1&amp;loop=0&amp;autoPlay=0&amp;permalink=1&amp;muted=0&amp;controls=1&amp;playsinline=0&amp;useAverageColor=0&amp;preloadContent=metadata' frameborder='0' allowfullscreen data-resize-to-parent=\"true\" allow='clipboard-write'></iframe><script data-jetpack-boost=\"ignore\" src='https://s0.wp.com/wp-content/plugins/video/assets/js/next/videopress-iframe.js'></script></div>\n<p>Bruce may not have remembered what Berry opened with that night, but their second song was &#8220;Rock and Roll Music,&#8221; one of Berry&#8217;s greatest hits.</p>\n<div class=\"jetpack-video-wrapper\"><span class=\"embed-youtube\" style=\"text-align:center; display: block;\"><iframe loading=\"lazy\" class=\"youtube-player\" width=\"758\" height=\"427\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/2wOZbMjzJsQ?version=3&#038;rel=1&#038;showsearch=0&#038;showinfo=1&#038;iv_load_policy=1&#038;fs=1&#038;hl=en-US&#038;autohide=2&#038;wmode=transparent\" allowfullscreen=\"true\" style=\"border:0;\" sandbox=\"allow-scripts allow-same-origin allow-popups allow-presentation allow-popups-to-escape-sandbox\"></iframe></span></div>\n<p>Berry took &#8220;Rock and Roll Music&#8221; to #8 on the Billboard Hot 100 in 1957, but it wasn&#8217;t just a hit for the original artist. The Beatles took it to the top of the charts in Europe in 1965&#8230;</p>\n<div class=\"jetpack-video-wrapper\"><span class=\"embed-youtube\" style=\"text-align:center; display: block;\"><iframe loading=\"lazy\" class=\"youtube-player\" width=\"758\" height=\"427\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/5gbb1gLhI3o?version=3&#038;rel=1&#038;showsearch=0&#038;showinfo=1&#038;iv_load_policy=1&#038;fs=1&#038;hl=en-US&#038;autohide=2&#038;wmode=transparent\" allowfullscreen=\"true\" style=\"border:0;\" sandbox=\"allow-scripts allow-same-origin allow-popups allow-presentation allow-popups-to-escape-sandbox\"></iframe></span></div>\n<p>&#8230;and The Beach Boys took it to #5 in the U.S. in the summer of &#8217;76.</p>\n<div class=\"jetpack-video-wrapper\"><span class=\"embed-youtube\" style=\"text-align:center; display: block;\"><iframe loading=\"lazy\" class=\"youtube-player\" width=\"758\" height=\"427\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/xzyLAfOGc4U?version=3&#038;rel=1&#038;showsearch=0&#038;showinfo=1&#038;iv_load_policy=1&#038;fs=1&#038;hl=en-US&#038;autohide=2&#038;wmode=transparent\" allowfullscreen=\"true\" style=\"border:0;\" sandbox=\"allow-scripts allow-same-origin allow-popups allow-presentation allow-popups-to-escape-sandbox\"></iframe></span></div>\n<p>But it&#8217;s the original version that endures.\u00a0<em>Rolling Stone\u00a0</em>ranked it #128 on their 500 Greatest Songs of All Time list, and the Rock and Roll Hall of Fame includes it in their 500 Songs That Shaped Rock and Roll.</p>\n<p>Unfortunately, no recording circulates (if it exists at all) of Bruce and Chuck&#8217;s first performance together, but we do have a great video of Bruce&#8217;s second-ever public performance of &#8220;Rock and Roll Music.&#8221;</p>\n<p>The date was December 13, 1987, the venue was Madison Square Garden, and the occasion was Paul Simon&#8217;s All Star Benefit for the Homeless Children. Paul assembled a truly stellar line-up for the occasion, and they all took the stage for the &#8220;Rock and Roll Music&#8221; finale.</p>\n<p>Paul Simon, Billy Joel, and James Taylor all took turns on lead vocals, but it was Bruce who served as the ensemble&#8217;s true frontman&#8211;and it went over so well that Bruce launched them into a reprise that lasted almost as long as their first go.</p>\n<div id=\"v-OoSDUzQr-1\" class=\"video-player\"><iframe title='VideoPress Video Player' aria-label='VideoPress Video Player' width='758' height='568' src='https://videopress.com/embed/OoSDUzQr?hd=1&amp;cover=1&amp;loop=0&amp;autoPlay=0&amp;permalink=1&amp;muted=0&amp;controls=1&amp;playsinline=0&amp;useAverageColor=0&amp;preloadContent=metadata' frameborder='0' allowfullscreen data-resize-to-parent=\"true\" allow='clipboard-write'></iframe><script data-jetpack-boost=\"ignore\" src='https://s0.wp.com/wp-content/plugins/video/assets/js/next/videopress-iframe.js'></script></div>\n<p>Bruce did get to perform &#8220;Rock and Roll Music&#8221; once more with Berry&#8211;at the finale of the Rock and Roll Hall of Fame inaugural concert in 1995. There were a lot more musicians on stage than the last time, but this time <em>everyone</em> knew who Bruce was.</p>\n<p><strong>Rock and Roll Music<br />\nFirst performed:\u00a0</strong>April 28, 1973 (College Park, MD)<br />\n<strong>Last performed:</strong> September 2, 1995 (Cleveland, OH)</p>\n<p>\u00a9 June 2, 2021</p>\n", "protected": false}, "excerpt": {"rendered": "<p>One time only: Bruce leads an all-star line-up on a raucous cover of Chuck Berry&#8217;s &#8220;Rock and Roll Music.&#8221;</p>\n", "protected": false}, "author": 1, "featured_media": 27656, "comment_status": "open", "ping_status": "open", "sticky": false, "template": "", "format": "standard", "meta": {"_monsterinsights_skip_tracking": false, "_monsterinsights_sitenote_active": false, "_monsterinsights_sitenote_note": "", "_monsterinsights_sitenote_category": 0, "_jetpack_newsletter_access": "", "_jetpack_dont_email_post_to_subs": false, "_jetpack_newsletter_tier_id": 0, "_jetpack_memberships_contains_paywalled_content": false, "_jetpack_memberships_contains_paid_content": false, "footnotes": "", "jetpack_publicize_message": "", "jetpack_publicize_feature_enabled": true, "jetpack_social_post_already_shared": true, "jetpack_social_options": {"image_generator_settings": {"template": "highway", "default_image_id": 0, "font": "", "enabled": false}, "version": 2}, "jetpack_post_was_ever_published": false}, "categories": [4, 3617, 5], "tags": [669, 155, 223, 670, 3204], "class_list": ["post-27052", "post", "type-post", "status-publish", "format-standard", "has-post-thumbnail", "hentry", "category-cover-me", "category-it-takes-two", "category-meeting-across-the-river", "tag-billy-joel", "tag-chuck-berry", "tag-james-taylor", "tag-paul-simon", "tag-rock-and-roll-music"], "aioseo_notices": [], "jetpack_publicize_connections": [], "jetpack_featured_media_url": "https://i0.wp.com/estreetshuffle.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/06/rrmusic.jpg?fit=1200%2C1182&ssl=1", "jetpack_sharing_enabled": true, "jetpack_shortlink": "https://wp.me/p9w3Lk-72k", "jetpack_likes_enabled": true, "jetpack-related-posts": [{"id": 341, "url": "https://estreetshuffle.com/index.php/1987/01/06/meeting-across-the-river-check-berry-bruce-springsteen-and-the-e-street-band/", "url_meta": {"origin": 27052, "position": 0}, "title": "Johnny B. Goode", "author": "Ken", "date": "January 6, 1987", "format": false, "excerpt": "From the 1995 opening concert for the Rock a